fields.name: Copy_1_of_AML_Corporate_Chceklist
fields.fieldText:
AML CHECKLIST 


For a KYC/AML verification of a Company, the following documents are typically required:


  • Certificate of Incorporation: To confirm the legal existence of the company.
  • Memorandum and Articles of Association: To understand the companys nature of business and operational guidelines.
  • Register of Shareholders: To identify the owners of the company.
  • Register of Directors: To identify those who have control over the company.
  • Identification of Beneficiaries and does who exercise control over the company: Identification of all of the ultimate beneficiaries. This can be in the form of a passport, driver's license, or other government-issued IDs.
  • Confirmation of registered office and trading address (if different): Such as a recent utility bill or lease agreement for the company's physical location.

fields.name: AMl_Individual_Checklist
fields.fieldText:
AML CHECKLIST 


For a KYC/AML verification of an individual, the following documents are typically required:


Identity Verification

  • Government-Issued Photo ID: Such as a passport, driver's license, or national ID card to verify the identity of the individual.

Address Verification

  • Utility Bills: Recent (within 3 months) bills for services such as water, gas, electricity, or landline phone to confirm the residential address.
  • Bank Statement: A recent statement can also serve as proof of address.
  • Government Correspondence: Any recent correspondence from a government authority indicating the individual's address.

fields.name: AML_Trust_Chceklist
fields.fieldText:
AML CHECKLIST 


For a KYC/AML verification of a trust, the following documents are typically required:


  • Trust Deed: This is the primary document that outlines the purpose, terms, and conditions of the trust. It includes details about the settlor, trustees, and beneficiaries.
  • Identification of Settlor(s): This can be a passport, driver's license, or any other government-issued ID.
  • Identification of Trustee(s): Similar to the settlor, a government-issued ID for each trustee is required.
  • Identification of Beneficiaries: Depending on the jurisdiction and the nature of the trust, identification of all or some of the beneficiaries might be required. This can be in the form of a passport, driver's license, or other government-issued IDs.
  • Proof of Address: This can be utility bills, bank statements, or any other document that verifies the address of the settlor, trustees, and sometimes beneficiaries.
  • Source of Funds: Documentation that provides evidence of the origin of the funds or assets that are being placed into the trust. This could include bank statements, sale agreements, or other relevant documents.
  • Details of the Trust's Assets: This includes information about the assets the trust holds, such as real estate, stocks, bonds, etc.
  • Business or Occupation Details: Information about the business or occupation of the settlor and trustees.
  • Purpose and Objective of the Trust: A detailed description of why the trust was established.
  • Tax Identification Number (TIN) or Equivalent: Depending on the jurisdiction, the trust's tax identification number or its equivalent might be required.
